home and those recovering from Coronavirus.";i:27;s:201:"Exercise 4 Chair Marching First check your posture Lift alternate legs so that your feet lift about 2 inches from the floor and swing your arms forwards and back at a speed that is comfortable for you.";i:28;s:43:"Imagine you marching along at a brisk pace.";i:29;s:85:"Continue for about 20 30 seconds Benefits Improves circulation and warms the muscles.";i:30;s:122:"With your back and legs straight and feet shoulder width apart slowly bend backwards supporting your back with your hands.";i:31;s:75:"As you increase the stretch work into the movement to loosen off your back.";i:32;s:63:"Hold for as long as is comfortable and then return to standing.";i:33;s:21:"Back bend from lying.";i:34;s:89:"For the exercises that require a chair chose one that is stable solid and without wheels.";i:35;s:85:"You should be able to sit with feet flat on the floor and knees bent at right angles.";i:36;s:59:"Avoid chairs with arms as this will restrict your movement.";i:37;s:58:"Wear loose comfortable clothing and keep some water handy.";i:38;s:46:"Wwwuhsnhsuk Side bend Sit on a chair Option 1.";i:39;s:42:"Cross your arms over the top of your head.";i:40;s:62:"Lean to the left and hold and then lean to the right and hold.";i:41;s:63:"Raise your right arm above your head lean to the left and hold.";i:42;s:41:"Swap arms and then lean to the right and.";i:43;s:121:"Work towards pushing up from sitting in a chair to a standing position without using a walker or leaning on someone else.";i:44;s:66:"Sit on a chair without arm rests with your arms across your chest.";i:45;s:51:"Put your weight on your feet while leaning forward.";i:46;s:37:"Stand up by straightening your knees.";i:47;s:43:"Repeat this as many times as you feel able.";i:48;s:35:"Marten High Back NHS Patient Chair.";i:49;s:119:"Many of our chairs are also available with a range of optional extras in the form of upholstered arms and filled sides.";i:50;s:117:"This means that for those patients with weaker legs the upper body can be used to assist them to a standing position.";i:51;s:48:"Other useful additions to our range of hospital.";i:52;s:77:"How to perform the exercises There are 2 types of exercises that can be done.";i:53;s:156:"The lower extremity exercise help to work your muscles from the below the waist and the upper extremity exercises help to work your muscles above the waist.";i:54;s:86:"In order to get the best results you will need to be committed to doing the exercises.";i:55;s:85:"Sit firmly in the back of a chair keep your shoulders down and maintain good posture.";i:56;s:71:"With or without an ankle weight slowly extend your leg in front of you.";i:57;s:34:"Repeat up to 10 times on each leg.";i:58;s:130:"Hip-strengthening exercises can help to build good leg muscle strength which will help you get out of the car or bath more easily.";i:59;s:52:"Gentle chair-based exercise for the elderly at home.";i:60;s:208:"Ryan Hughes is the Physical Activity Project Officer for the Mobile Me programme run by Active Norfolk which focuses on the over 65s and is designed to address barriers to participation within this age group.";i:61;s:121:"In terms of exercise in the home we like to emphasise that every little bit of activity an older person can do will have.";i:62;s:154:"T o exercise the muscle at the back of the thigh place your hands on a chair or table for support and move your sore leg slightly back from the other leg.";i:63;s:118:"Bend your knee and lift your back foot off the floor - you should feel the muscle tightening at the back of the thigh.";i:64;s:57:"Hold for 2 seconds then return to your starting position.";i:65;s:111:"Reducing sarcopenia in older adults and improving wellbeing through targeted chair -based resistance exercises.";i:66;s:148:"Pilot - May to December 2016 PDF This report sets out the findings of a pilot that look place from May to December 2016 in four locations in the UK.";i:67;s:37:"Banbury Leicester Oxford and Suffolk.";i:68;s:76:"Chair exercises for seniors are easy safe and able to be performed anywhere.";i:69;s:69:"These 21 chair exercises come with steps visuals and videos for each.";i:70;s:181:"Chair-bound exercises are ideal for people with lower body injuries or disabilities those with weight problems or diabetes and frail seniors looking to reduce their risk of falling.";i:71;s:158:"Cardiovascular and flexibility chair exercises can help improve posture and reduce back pain while any chair exercise can help alleviate body sores caused by.";}}